Let $G$ denote a set of invertible $2 times 2$ matrices (matrices with complex
numbers as entries and determinant nonzero) with the property that if $a, b$
are in $G$, then so are $a b$ and $a^(-1)$. Suppose there exists a function $f
: G -> RR$ with the property that either $f(g a) > f(a)$ or $f(g^(-1) a) >
f(a)$ for all $a, g$ in $G$ with $g != I$ (here $I$ denotes the identity
matrix, $RR$ denotes the real numbers, and the inequality signs are strict
inequality). Prove that given finite nonempty subsets $A, B$ of $G$, there is a
matrix in $G$ which can be written in exactly one way in the form $x y$ with
$x$ in $A$ and $y$ in $B$.
